outcomes.title: Terms and factors
outcomes.description: I can identify terms and factors. I can combine like terms and factor out common factors.
outcomes.template:
Consider the expression {{sum}}.

Combine like terms, as much as possible.

Which terms have common factors? Tell me what the common factors are.

{{result}}

{{term0}} and {{term1}} share a common factor of {{factor0}}. {{term2}} and {{term3}} share a common factor of {{factor1}}.

outcomes.title: Generating circular functions
outcomes.description: I can generate an accurate, labeled graph of a circular function given appropriate information about the circle being traversed, and describe key features of the function.
outcomes.template:
Consider the circle centered at the point {{center}} whose circumference is {{circumference}}. Let h = f(d) be the circular function that tracks the height, h, of a point traversing the circle {{direction}} by starting at the point P_0, where d is the distance the point is along the circle from P_0. Find the exact coordinates of 4 points on the circle, and give your best guess for two more. Then, sketch an accurate graph of h = f(d), clearly labeling at least 6 different points on the function, and state the midline, amplitude, and period of the function. Provide a written summary of your computations and thinking.

Here are some important things that will help us figure out points on this circle:

Since the circumference is {{circumference}}, the period of f(d) is {{circumference}}.

The distance between each point marked on the circle is \frac{{{circumference}}}{8} = {{deltad}}.

Since the circle is centered at {{center}}, the midline of f(d) is y = {{yc}}.

Since the circumference is {{circumference}}, the radius is \frac{ {{circumference}} }{2\pi} \approx {{radius}}. This will be the amplitude of f(d).

(Note that this graph is incomplete because it doesn't have points labeled on it!)

outcomes.title: Fitting exponential functions
outcomes.description: I can find the formula for an exponential function given two data points.
outcomes.template:
Determine exact values for a and b so that the exponential function g(t) = ab^t passes through the points \left({{t1}}, {{y1}}\right) and \left({{t2}}, {{y2}}\right). Show all of your work and thinking fully.

Partial answer:

b = \left( \frac{ {{y2}} }{ {{y1}} } \right)^{1/{{deltat}} }

a = \frac{ {{y1}} }{ ({{y2}} / {{y1}})^{ {{t1}}/{{deltat}} } }

g(t) = \frac{ {{y1}} }{ ({{y2}} / {{y1}})^{ {{t1}}/{{deltat}} } } \cdot \left( \left( \frac{ {{y2}} }{ {{y1}} } \right)^{1/{{deltat}} } \right)^t

outcomes.title: Features of exponential functions
outcomes.description: I can describe the long-term behavior of an exponential function or a transformed version of an exponential function. I can tell whether the function is increasing, decreasing, concave up, or concave down.
outcomes.template:
Consider a function of the form f(t) = c \pm a b^t. By selecting positive constants a, b, and c and choosing appropiately from the \pm sign, give an example* of such a function that has the following properties:

f is always {{creasing}},

f is always {{concave}},

as {{limdir}}, f(t) \to {{lim}}.

Explain how you know that your choices for a, b, and c produce a function with the correct properties.

(* Note: there are many, many choices that work; you just need to think about the characteristics of the function f and what you need to be true of a, b, and c.)

Partial answer:

The \pm must be {{pm}}.

We need {{growdec}}.

c must equal {{lim}}.

outcomes.title: Using exponential and logarithmic expressions
outcomes.description: I can solve equations involving exponential and logarithmic expressions. I can apply the properties of exponential and logarithmic functions to simplify expressions.
outcomes.template:
Find the exact solution (no squequals, please!) to each of the following equations, writing your solution in terms of exponential or logarithmic expressions appropriately. Show your steps and thinking clearly.

{{parta}}

\let\log\relax \newcommand{\log}{\ln} {{partb}}

Solve the following equation for t in terms of y: {{partc}}

Partial answer:

t = \frac{\ln\left(\frac{ {{dminusa}} }{c}\right)} { {{m}} \cdot \ln\left( {{q}} \right) } - \frac{ {{b}} }{ {{m}} }

t = \frac{1}{ {{m}} } \left(e^{ {{RminusC}} / {{A}} } - {{B}} \right)

t = \frac{1}{ {{k}} }\cdot \ln\left( \frac{y - {{V}} }{ {{P}} } \right)

Part (b):

In a right triangle with legs with length {{leg1}} and {{leg2}} and hypotenuse {{hyp}}, find the sine, cosine, and tangent of the smaller of the two non-right angles. Draw a picture!

Part (a):

outcomes.title: Solving right triangle puzzles
outcomes.description: Given a right triangle with partial information about its sides and angles, I can determine the missing information for the remaining sides and angles.
outcomes.template:
For each of the following parts, draw and clearly label a picture, and use that picture to find the exact values of the missing pieces of the right triangle. No squequals, please!

Part (a):

In a certain right triangle, one angle measures {{angle1A}} radians and {{sideA}} has length {{length1A}}. Find the exact measure of the non-right angle and the exact lengths of the other two sides.

Part (b):

In a given right triangle, {{side1B}} has length {{length1B}} and {{side2B}} has length {{length2B}}. Find the exact length of the remaining side and both exact and approximate measures of the two non-right angles (both in radians).

Part (c):

Consider the right triangle with hypotenuse {{hypC}}, horizontal leg {{adjC}}, and vertical leg {{oppC}}, with angle \theta opposite the vertical leg. How can we view {{v1}} as depending on {{v2}} only? How can we view {{v1}} as depending on \theta only?

Partial answer:

Part (a):

The side adjacent to the given angle is {{adjA}}. The side opposite to the given angle is {{oppA}}. The hypotenuse is {{hypA}}. The other non-right angle is {{angle2A}}.

Part (b):

The two legs have length {{adjB}} and {{oppB}}. The hypotenuse has length {{hypB}}. The two angles are {{angle1B}} and {{angle2B}}

Part (c):

{{v1}} = {{ans1C}}, and {{v1}} = {{ans2C}}.
